# Meta-Repository Spec Management

## Context

This repository uses a meta-repo pattern for spec-driven development:
- Specs organized by type (feature/bug/chore/design/planning)
- Each spec has: .spec.md, .plan.md, context/, context/scratch/, repo/
- Three-tier memory system (org/project/repo + scratch)
- YAML front matter for metadata tracking

## Directory Structure

```
specs/{type}/{id}-{name}/
├── {id}-{name}.spec.md    # Functional specification
├── {id}-{name}.plan.md    # Technical implementation plan
├── context/               # Curated context
│   └── scratch/           # Volatile working memory (gitignored)
└── repo/                  # Cloned repositories (gitignored)
```

## When Creating New Specs

1. Choose spec type: feature, bug, chore, design, planning
2. Use naming convention: `specs/{type}/{id}-{name}/`
   - {id} is optional (for ticket mapping)
   - {name} should be kebab-case
3. Copy templates from `docs/templates/`
4. Update YAML front matter (dates, status, type, priority)
5. Create subdirectories: `context/scratch/`, `repo/`

## When Working Within a Spec

- Clone repos into `spec-dir/repo/` (gitignored in meta-repo)
- **Create a feature branch** in each cloned repo that mirrors the meta-repo branch name before making changes
- Use `context/scratch/` for volatile working notes
- Reference cloned repo docs: `spec-dir/repo/{project}/AGENTS.md`
- Commit changes within cloned repos, not meta-repo — always on a feature branch, never the default branch
- Use spec context/ for curated reference material

## Memory Promotion

When completing a spec, analyze and promote valuable context:

### From scratch to permanent:
- Review `context/scratch/` for valuable insights
- Analyze git changes for architectural decisions
- Promote to appropriate tier:
  - Spec `context/` - Reference material for this spec
  - `architecture/` - C4 diagrams, architectural decisions
  - `requirements/` - PRDs, requirements docs
  - `project/` - Project briefs, charters
- Delete temporary scratch notes

### From git changes:
- Look for new patterns/conventions in code
- Identify architectural decisions
- Note dependencies added/removed
- Document API contracts or interfaces
- These may warrant architecture or requirements docs

## Available Commands

- `/new-spec` - Create new spec with templates
- `/list-specs` - Show all specs by type/status
- `/sync-repo` - Clone/update repos for a spec
- `/analyze-scratch` - Review scratch and git changes for promotion
- `/archive-spec` - Archive completed spec with cleanup

